04978nam a22007095i 9780804793476DE-B159720201125033335.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201125t20202014cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2014011924  a97808047934767 a10.1515/97808047934762doi  a(DE-B1597)564825  a(OCoLC)1224278018  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aPN1993.5.K6bP37 2015 4aPN1993.5.K6b.P37 2015eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a791.43095195223  aLC 954452rvk0(DE-625)rvk/90707:9091 aPark, Young-a, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnexpected Alliances :bIndependent Filmmakers, the State, and the Film Industry in Postauthoritarian South Korea /cYoung-a Park. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote to Readers -- tAcronyms -- tIntroduction -- t1. Film Activism: Cinema as Politics -- t2. Independent Film: Cultural Production under Postauthoritarian Conditions -- t3. Beating Titanic: Independent Filmmakers at the Helm of Cultural Nationalism -- t4. Transforming Activist Culture: Women Filmmakers and New Filmic Spaces -- t5. Film Festival Fever: The Circulation of Independent Films -- tEpilogue: New Cultural Spaces, New Sensibilities -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tSelected Filmography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince 1999, South Korean films have dominated roughly 40 to 60 percent of the Korean domestic box-office, matching or even surpassing Hollywood films in popularity. Why is this, and how did it come about? In Unexpected Alliances, Young-a Park seeks to answer these questions by exploring the cultural and institutional roots of the Korean film industry's phenomenal success in the context of Korea's political transition in the late 1990s and early 2000s. The book investigates the unprecedented interplay between independent filmmakers, the state, and the mainstream film industry under the post-authoritarian administrations of Kim Dae Jung (1998-2003) and Roh Moo Hyun (2003-2008), and shows how these alliances were critical in the making of today's Korean film industry. During South Korea's post-authoritarian reform era, independent filmmakers with activist backgrounds were able to mobilize and transform themselves into important players in state cultural institutions and in negotiations with the purveyors of capital. Instead of simply labeling the alliances "selling out" or "co-optation," this book explores the new spaces, institutions, and conversations which emerged and shows how independent filmmakers played a key role in national protests against trade liberalization, actively contributing to the creation of the very idea of a "Korean national cinema" worthy of protection. Independent filmmakers changed not only the film institutions and policies but the ways in which people produce, consume, and think about film in South Korea.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Nov 2020) 0aIndependent filmmakerszKorea (South) 0aIndependent filmmakerszKorea (South). 0aIndependent filmsxPolitical aspectszKorea (South) 0aIndependent filmsxPolitical aspectszKorea (South). 0aMotion picture industryzKorea (South) 0aMotion picture industryzKorea (South). 0aPolitics and culturezKorea (South) 0aPolitics and culturezKorea (South). 4aSouth Korea. 4aactivism. 4aalliances. 4aco-optation. 4ademocratic generation/3-8-6 generation. 4afilm industry. 4aindependent filmmakers. 4apostauthoritarian state. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps: